ion intended to eliminate these strains. Conrad also explores the strains of colonial life, but from a perspective antithetical in many respects to Kipling's. In the Lingard novels and Lord Jim he challenges the imperial image of the colonialist as a wise, benign father protecting his savage dependents. The pessimistic assessment of the colonialist's motives and achievements developed in these works finds full expression, McClure suggests, in Heart of Darkness. And in Nostromo Conrad explores the human dimensions of large-scale capitalist intervention in the colonial world,, finding once again no cause to celebrate imperialism. John McClure's interpretation is forceful but ever attuned to the complexities of the texts discussed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aColonies in literature. 0aEngels. 0aEnglische Literatur. 0aFictie. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aKolonialisme. 0aPolitical fiction, English. 4aColonies in literature. 4aConrad, Joseph, 1857-1924 -- Criticism and interpretation. 4aEnglish fiction -- History and criticism. 4aImperialism in literature. 4aKipling, Rudyard, 1865-1936 -- Criticism and interpretation. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Literature eBook Packagez9783110353501oZDB-23-HLI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067442862140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067442863840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674428638423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674428638.jpg  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKA